('p8', 203, 'Biology History', '<h2 style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 1em 0px 0.25em; padding: 0px; overflow: hidden; border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177); font-size: 1.5em; font-family: &quot;Linux Libertine&quot;, Georgia, Times, serif; line-height: 1.3;\"><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span></h2><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\" style=\"font-style: italic; padding-left: 1.6em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Further information:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_biology\" title=\"History of biology\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">History of biology</a></div><div class=\"thumb tright\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; width: auto; margin: 0.5em 0px 1.3em 1.4em; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"min-width: 100px; padding: 3px; text-align: center; overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid rgb(200, 204, 209); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); font-size: 13.16px; width: 222px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hooke-bluefly.jpg\" class=\"image\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><img alt=\"A drawing of a fly from facing up, with wing detail\" src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Hooke-bluefly.jpg/220px-Hooke-bluefly.jpg\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"220\" height=\"334\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Hooke-bluefly.jpg/330px-Hooke-bluefly.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Hooke-bluefly.jpg/440px-Hooke-bluefly.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1176\" data-file-height=\"1786\" style=\"border: 1px solid rgb(200, 204, 209); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\"></a><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"text-align: left; line-height: 1.4em; padding: 3px; border: 0px; font-size: 12.3704px;\"><div class=\"magnify\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 3px; margin-right: 0px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hooke-bluefly.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: url(&quot;/w/resources/src/mediawiki.skinning/images/magnify-clip-ltr.svg?8330e&quot;); background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; display: block; text-indent: 15px; white-space: nowrap; overflow: hidden; width: 15px; height: 11px; user-select: none;\"></a></div>Diagram of a fly from&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Hooke\" title=\"Robert Hooke\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Robert Hooke</a>\'s innovative&nbsp;<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micrographia\" title=\"Micrographia\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Micrographia</a></i>, 1665</div></div></div><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The earliest of roots of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science\" title=\"Science\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">science</a>, which included&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine\" title=\"Medicine\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">medicine</a>, can be traced to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt\" title=\"Ancient Egypt\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">ancient Egypt</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia\" title=\"Mesopotamia\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Mesopotamia</a>&nbsp;in around 3000 to 1200&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Era\" title=\"Common Era\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">BCE</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Lindberg1_15-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Lindberg1-15\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[15]</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Grant2007a_16-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Grant2007a-16\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[16]</a></sup>&nbsp;Their contributions later entered and shaped Greek&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_philosophy\" title=\"Natural philosophy\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">natural philosophy</a>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_antiquity\" title=\"Classical antiquity\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">classical antiquity</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Lindberg1_15-1\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Lindberg1-15\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[15]</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Grant2007a_16-1\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Grant2007a-16\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[16]</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-17\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-17\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[17]</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-18\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-18\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[18]</a></sup>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece\" title=\"Ancient Greece\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Ancient Greek</a>&nbsp;philosophers such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle\" title=\"Aristotle\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Aristotle</a>&nbsp;(384–322 BCE) contributed extensively to the development of biological knowledge. His works such as&nbsp;<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Animals\" title=\"History of Animals\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">History of Animals</a></i>&nbsp;were especially important because they revealed his naturalist leanings, and later more empirical works that focused on biological causation and the diversity of life. Aristotle\'s successor at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyceum\" title=\"Lyceum\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Lyceum</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theophrastus\" title=\"Theophrastus\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Theophrastus</a>, wrote a series of books on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Botany\" title=\"Botany\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">botany</a>&nbsp;that survived as the most important contribution of antiquity to the plant sciences, even into the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ages\" title=\"Middle Ages\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Middle Ages</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-eb1911_19-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-eb1911-19\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[19]</a></sup></p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Scholars of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world\" title=\"Science in the medieval Islamic world\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">medieval Islamic world</a>&nbsp;who wrote on biology included&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Jahiz\" title=\"Al-Jahiz\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">al-Jahiz</a>&nbsp;(781–869),&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-D%C4%ABnawar%C4%AB\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Al-Dīnawarī\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Al-Dīnawarī</a>&nbsp;(828–896), who wrote on botany,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Fahd-815_20-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Fahd-815-20\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[20]</a></sup>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad_ibn_Zakar%C4%ABya_R%C4%81zi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Muhammad ibn Zakarīya Rāzi\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Rhazes</a>&nbsp;(865–925) who wrote on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anatomy\" title=\"Anatomy\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">anatomy</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physiology\" title=\"Physiology\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">physiology</a>.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine\" title=\"Medicine\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Medicine</a>&nbsp;was especially well studied by Islamic scholars working in Greek philosopher traditions, while natural history drew heavily on Aristotelian thought, especially in upholding a fixed hierarchy of life.</p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Biology began to quickly develop and grow with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton_van_Leeuwenhoek\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Anton van Leeuwenhoek\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Anton van Leeuwenhoek</a>\'s dramatic improvement of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microscope\" title=\"Microscope\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">microscope</a>. It was then that scholars discovered&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spermatozoa\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Spermatozoa\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">spermatozoa</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteria\" title=\"Bacteria\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">bacteria</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infusoria\" title=\"Infusoria\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">infusoria</a>&nbsp;and the diversity of microscopic life. Investigations by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_Swammerdam\" title=\"Jan Swammerdam\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Jan Swammerdam</a>&nbsp;led to new interest in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entomology\" title=\"Entomology\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">entomology</a>&nbsp;and helped to develop the basic techniques of microscopic&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dissection\" title=\"Dissection\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">dissection</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Staining\" title=\"Staining\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">staining</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-21\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-21\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[21]</a></sup></p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Advances in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microscopy\" title=\"Microscopy\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">microscopy</a>&nbsp;also had a profound impact on biological thinking. In the early 19th century, a number of biologists pointed to the central importance of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_(biology)\" title=\"Cell (biology)\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">cell</a>. Then, in 1838,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthias_Jakob_Schleiden\" title=\"Matthias Jakob Schleiden\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Schleiden</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodor_Schwann\" title=\"Theodor Schwann\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Schwann</a>&nbsp;began promoting the now universal ideas that (1) the basic unit of organisms is the cell and (2) that individual cells have all the characteristics of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life\" title=\"Life\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">life</a>, although they opposed the idea that (3) all cells come from the division of other cells. However,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Remak\" title=\"Robert Remak\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Robert Remak</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolf_Virchow\" title=\"Rudolf Virchow\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Rudolf Virchow</a>&nbsp;were able to reify the third tenet, and by the 1860s most biologists accepted all three tenets which consolidated into&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_theory\" title=\"Cell theory\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">cell theory</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-22\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-22\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[22]</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-23\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-23\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[23]</a></sup></p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Meanwhile, taxonomy and classification became the focus of natural historians.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Linnaeus\" title=\"Carl Linnaeus\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Carl Linnaeus</a>&nbsp;published a basic&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxonomy_(biology)\" title=\"Taxonomy (biology)\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">taxonomy</a>&nbsp;for the natural world in 1735 (variations of which have been in use ever since), and in the 1750s introduced&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_nomenclature\" title=\"Binomial nomenclature\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">scientific names</a>&nbsp;for all his species.<sup id=\"cite_ref-24\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-24\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[24]</a></sup>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georges-Louis_Leclerc,_Comte_de_Buffon\" title=\"Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon</a>, treated species as artificial categories and living forms as malleable—even suggesting the possibility of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_descent\" title=\"Common descent\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">common descent</a>. Although he was opposed to evolution, Buffon is a key figure in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_evolutionary_thought\" title=\"History of evolutionary thought\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">history of evolutionary thought</a>; his work influenced the evolutionary theories of both&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamarck\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lamarck\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Lamarck</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Darwin\" title=\"Charles Darwin\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Darwin</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-25\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-25\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[25]</a></sup></p><div class=\"thumb tright\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; width: auto; margin: 0.5em 0px 1.3em 1.4em; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"min-width: 100px; padding: 3px; text-align: center; overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid rgb(200, 204, 209); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); font-size: 13.16px; width: 222px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg\" class=\"image\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg/220px-Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"220\" height=\"269\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg/330px-Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/42/Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"398\" data-file-height=\"487\" style=\"border: 1px solid rgb(200, 204, 209); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\"></a><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"text-align: left; line-height: 1.4em; padding: 3px; border: 0px; font-size: 12.3704px;\"><div class=\"magnify\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 3px; margin-right: 0px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Charles_Darwin_aged_51.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: url(&quot;/w/resources/src/mediawiki.skinning/images/magnify-clip-ltr.svg?8330e&quot;); background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; display: block; text-indent: 15px; white-space: nowrap; overflow: hidden; width: 15px; height: 11px; user-select: none;\"></a></div>In 1842,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Darwin\" title=\"Charles Darwin\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Charles Darwin</a>&nbsp;penned his first sketch of&nbsp;<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_the_Origin_of_Species\" title=\"On the Origin of Species\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">On the Origin of Species</a></i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-26\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 9.89632px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-26\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[26]</a></sup></div></div></div><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Serious evolutionary thinking originated with the works of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Baptiste_Lamarck\" title=\"Jean-Baptiste Lamarck\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Jean-Baptiste Lamarck</a>, who was the first to present a coherent theory of evolution.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gould_2002_187_27-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Gould_2002_187-27\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[27]</a></sup>&nbsp;He posited that evolution was the result of environmental stress on properties of animals, meaning that the more frequently and rigorously an organ was used, the more complex and efficient it would become, thus adapting the animal to its environment. Lamarck believed that these acquired traits could then be passed on to the animal\'s offspring, who would further develop and perfect them.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Lam1914_28-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Lam1914-28\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[28]</a></sup>&nbsp;However, it was the British naturalist&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Darwin\" title=\"Charles Darwin\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Charles Darwin</a>, combining the biogeographical approach of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_von_Humboldt\" title=\"Alexander von Humboldt\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Humboldt</a>, the uniformitarian geology of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Lyell\" title=\"Charles Lyell\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Lyell</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Malthus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Thomas Malthus\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Malthus\'s</a>&nbsp;writings on population growth, and his own morphological expertise and extensive natural observations, who forged a more successful evolutionary theory based on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_selection\" title=\"Natural selection\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">natural selection</a>; similar reasoning and evidence led&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Russel_Wallace\" title=\"Alfred Russel Wallace\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Alfred Russel Wallace</a>&nbsp;to independently reach the same conclusions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-29\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-29\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[29]</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-30\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-30\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[30]</a></sup>&nbsp;Darwin\'s theory of evolution by natural selection quickly spread through the scientific community and soon became a central axiom of the rapidly developing science of biology.</p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(32, 33, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The basis for modern genetics began with the work of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregor_Mendel\" title=\"Gregor Mendel\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Gregor Mendel</a>, who presented his paper, \"<i>Versuche über Pflanzenhybriden</i>\" (\"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experiments_on_Plant_Hybridization\" title=\"Experiments on Plant Hybridization\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Experiments on Plant Hybridization</a>\"), in 1865,<sup id=\"cite_ref-31\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-31\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[31]</a></sup>&nbsp;which outlined the principles of biological inheritance, serving as the basis for modern genetics.<sup id=\"cite_ref-miko2008a_32-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-miko2008a-32\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[32]</a></sup>&nbsp;However, the significance of his work was not realized until the early 20th century when evolution became a unified theory as the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_synthesis_(20th_century)\" title=\"Modern synthesis (20th century)\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">modern synthesis</a>&nbsp;reconciled Darwinian evolution with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_genetics\" title=\"Classical genetics\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">classical genetics</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Futuyma2017a_33-0\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-Futuyma2017a-33\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[33]</a></sup>&nbsp;In the 1940s and early 1950s, a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hershey%E2%80%93Chase_experiment\" title=\"Hershey–Chase experiment\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">series of experiments</a>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Hershey\" title=\"Alfred Hershey\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Alfred Hershey</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martha_Chase\" title=\"Martha Chase\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Martha Chase</a>&nbsp;pointed to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA\" title=\"DNA\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">DNA</a>&nbsp;as the component of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromosomes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Chromosomes\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">chromosomes</a>&nbsp;that held the trait-carrying units that had become known as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Genes\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">genes</a>. A focus on new kinds of model organisms such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viruses\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Viruses\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">viruses</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteria\" title=\"Bacteria\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">bacteria</a>, along with the discovery of the double-helical structure of DNA by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Watson\" title=\"James Watson\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">James Watson</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Crick\" title=\"Francis Crick\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Francis Crick</a>&nbsp;in 1953, marked the transition to the era of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_genetics\" title=\"Molecular genetics\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">molecular genetics</a>. From the 1950s onwards, biology has been vastly extended in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_Biology\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Molecular Biology\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">molecular</a>&nbsp;domain. The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_code\" title=\"Genetic code\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">genetic code</a>&nbsp;was cracked by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Har_Gobind_Khorana\" title=\"Har Gobind Khorana\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Har Gobind Khorana</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_W._Holley\" title=\"Robert W. Holley\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Robert W. Holley</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marshall_Warren_Nirenberg\" title=\"Marshall Warren Nirenberg\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Marshall Warren Nirenberg</a>&nbsp;after DNA was understood to contain&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Codons\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Codons\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">codons</a>. Finally, the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_Genome_Project\" title=\"Human Genome Project\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Human Genome Project</a>&nbsp;was launched in 1990 with the goal of mapping the general human&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genome\" title=\"Genome\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">genome</a>. This project was essentially completed in 2003,<sup id=\"cite_ref-34\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology#cite_note-34\" style=\"color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[34]</a></sup>&nbsp;with further analysis still being published. The Human Genome Project was the first step in a globalized effort to incorporate accumulated knowledge of biology into a functional, molecular definition of the human body and the bodies of other organisms.</p><div><br></div> ', 103, NULL, '', 1, 0, '', '', NULL, '2022-05-25 19:32:39');
